00:43:51.880 --> 00:43:55.580
of professional legal
work in my view.

00:43:55.580 --> 00:43:57.060
So, I wanted to hear your.

00:43:57.060 --> 00:43:59.510
&gt;&gt; Hilarie Bass: So, let me
take the first question about.

00:43:59.510 --> 00:44:00.810
&gt;&gt; The judiciary, yes.

00:44:00.810 --> 00:44:03.650
&gt;&gt; Hilarie Bass: So, obviously
every time you have an

00:44:03.650 --> 00:44:06.390
administration change, the
president has the ability

00:44:06.390 --> 00:44:09.380
to appoint judicial nominees.

00:44:09.380 --> 00:44:15.080
The ABA is involved in
a peer review process

00:44:15.080 --> 00:44:17.180
with every president
since Eisenhower.

00:44:17.180 --> 00:44:21.200
This president has us in the
post-nomination review process,

00:44:21.200 --> 00:44:24.930
but senate judiciary
still looks to the ABA

00:44:24.930 --> 00:44:28.140
to get our peer review report

00:44:28.140 --> 00:44:32.510
where we do a non-ideological
peer review,

00:44:32.510 --> 00:44:35.480
meaning we don't ask
people what their party is,

00:44:35.480 --> 00:44:39.160
whether they're conservatives or
liberals, we're looking purely

00:44:39.160 --> 00:44:41.630
at whether they have the
intellectual capacity

00:44:41.630 --> 00:44:44.930
to be a lifetime
appointment judge,

00:44:44.930 --> 00:44:46.230
whether they have
the temperament,

00:44:46.230 --> 00:44:49.340
and whether they have the
integrity and that process

00:44:49.340 --> 00:44:53.930
of peer review, remains constant
from president to president

00:44:53.930 --> 00:44:55.800
and I believe it's
one of the reasons

00:44:55.800 --> 00:44:58.630
that this Senate Judiciary
Committee relies upon our

00:44:58.630 --> 00:45:01.820
reports even if they don't
always agree with them,

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:06.480
because our committee does a
completely confidential review

00:45:06.480 --> 00:45:10.480
process, even I as president
of the ABA does not get access

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:15.750
to those reports, and they
literally call a 100 people

00:45:15.750 --> 00:45:18.670
everybody who's been,
has been an advisory

00:45:18.670 --> 00:45:22.150
to this judicial nominee,
they're law professors,

00:45:22.150 --> 00:45:25.310
they're the judges in front
of whom they've appeared

00:45:25.310 --> 00:45:28.140
to really get a full
perspective about whether

00:45:28.140 --> 00:45:30.400
or not this person has the
appropriate temperament

00:45:30.400 --> 00:45:33.950
and intellectual
capability irrespective

00:45:33.950 --> 00:45:36.120
of their ideological basis.

00:45:36.120 --> 00:45:40.480
So, is there more politics
in judicial selections

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:41.920
than there have been
in the past?

00:45:41.920 --> 00:45:44.660
Well, obviously anybody
who reviewed what happened

00:45:44.660 --> 00:45:47.580
in the last 6 months of
the Obama Administration

00:45:47.580 --> 00:45:50.650
with his inability to
fill a judicial vacancy

00:45:50.650 --> 00:45:52.450
on the Supreme Court
has to believe

00:45:52.450 --> 00:45:55.580
that politics have
infiltrated that process more

00:45:55.580 --> 00:46:01.500
than in the past, but the ABA
continues to endeavor to ensure

00:46:01.500 --> 00:46:05.460
that politics do not affect
their analysis of whether

00:46:05.460 --> 00:46:08.420
or not the person has the
appropriate intellectual

00:46:08.420 --> 00:46:10.990
capacity and integrity
to be a judge.

00:46:10.990 --> 00:46:13.670
ON the secondary issue
about technology,

00:46:13.670 --> 00:46:17.040
clearly what lawyers
do will change,

00:46:17.040 --> 00:46:20.760
with 80% of the population
being unrepresented,

00:46:20.760 --> 00:46:23.430
I don't believe there's going
to be a need for less lawyers.

00:46:23.430 --> 00:46:25.950
I do believe what lawyers
in the future will be asked

00:46:25.950 --> 00:46:29.860
to do will be different and not
everybody is going to be able

00:46:29.860 --> 00:46:33.870
to get into big law and
charge 700 dollars an hour.

00:46:33.870 --> 00:46:39.370
